This is a very clean architectural approach. By separating the concurrency orchestration from the actual integration logic, your code becomes much easier to test, maintain, and scale.
In this design, your new service acts as the "Orchestrator." It chops up the data, spins up the virtual threads, and delegates the actual work to your existing Salesforce service.
Here is how you can structure this, using standard Spring Boot @Service annotations to represent the two distinct components.
1. The Domain Objects
